flares.note: Close proximity between AR 14294 and 14296. Appears closer to AR 14294.
Concurrent brightening with AR 14294 that spans about 2025-12-08T22:22Z-T22:46Z in GOES SUVI 131 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the east in GOES CCOR-1 imagery, and to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to flipped imagery following a keyhole maneuver. This event is likely far-sided and therefore not observed in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption visible near the eastern limb in GOES SUVI 304 imagery which begins to lift off around 2025-12-03T01:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measured longitude based on the approximate source location. As this event is not observed in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not possible. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the northeast in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This event is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery in real-time due to flipped imagery following a keyhole maneuver. The source is likely related to a dimming region centered near N45E45 first visible around 2025-12-03T05:20Z in GOES SUVI 195 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely a filament eruption starting around 2025-12-03T10:30Z which spans S25W25 to S10W65 seen in GOES SUVI 131/171/195/284/304 and STEREO A EUVI 195/304 imagery. An opening of field lines can be observed over the western limb at this time and post eruptive arcades begin to form around 2025-12-03T14:00Z seen in GOES SUVI 195/304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is faint and likely a halo as observed by STEREO A, making

cmes.note: A narrower follow-up CME front following 2025-12-03T11:06Z CME and seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the north in STEREO A COR2. Its source could be a part of a very long filament eruption stretching from S20W25 to N20W70 and also associated with the 2025-12-03T11:06Z CME. Its front in STEREO A COR2 could be the second northern, faint halo (partial), following the earlier full halo associated with the 2025-12-03T11:06Z CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit of a very faint second halo in STEREO A COR2 with the rather messy follow-up to 2025-12-03T11:06Z CME, front seen in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Narrow faint CME to the E seen in GOES CCOR-1 and (after a data gap) in SOHO LASCO C3. Covered by a daily data gap in STEREO A. The source could be a faint movement of field lines far behind the E limb in GOES SUVI 195 around 2025-12-03T20Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: In the absence of STEREO A imagery and the absence of on-disk source (a faint potential far-sided source has been found) only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

cmes.note: Faint narrow pointy-nosed CME to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1. Start is likely earlier. The CME is covered by the daily gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source is possibly an eruption behind the NW limb starting at 2025-12-03T22:30Z and seen as opening/movement of field lines in GOES SUVI 195 and 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: In the absence of STEREO A imagery and the likely far-sided source only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

cmes.note:
CME: 2025-12-03T23:18Z (C3) SW 
Faint CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs and covered by a daily data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its start is likely much earlier (there is a temporary data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 currently). It source is possibly a minor movement of field lines (and possibly faint post-eruptive arcades) on/behind the SW limb seen in GOES SUVI 195 and 284 after 2025-12-03T19Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Because of the absence of STEREO A COR2 imagery for this CME and potential source being behind the limb, only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

cmes.note: This CME is faintly seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is no clear source for this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky best fit using SWPC_CAT and SOHO imagery. Event is faint, so there may be some uncertainty with speed.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is an M6.0 class flare from AR 14300 (N10E58) which peaked at 2025-12-04T02:50Z best observed in GOES SUVI 131. Additionally observed as wide field line movement/EUV wave in GOES SUVI 171/195/284, with some dimming around the region in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2, finding a good fit with some deflected away from the observed flare source at N10E58.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2, wispy front that becomes more defined further into the coronagraph's field-of-view. The source may be observed as field line movement to the NE in GOES SUVI 284, it is not clear where this traces to on the disk but it may be outflow following the M6.0 from AR 14300 (N10E58), which peaked at 2025-12-04T02:50Z, that is associated with CME 2025-12-04T03:24Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The CME distorts and expands from early frames in LASCO C2, so only later frames in C3 and COR2A are used when it takes its more final shape.

cmes.note: Bright, wide CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely slow, wide field line movement beginning around 2025-12-04T04:30Z in GOES SUVI 195/284, with brightening in GOES SUVI 171/195, centered around S21E48.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear and the best candidate may be a small filament eruption to the NE in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-12-04T07:40Z centered around N30E50, but this is a large deflection to the observed CME, so it is unlikely.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Narrow, odd shaped, faint event to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. There isn't a clear source for this CME but may be associated with outflow along the western limb or ejecta material from AR 14298 (S16W05).

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on plane-of-sky fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery in SWPC_CAT.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen only in a few frames to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and possibly to the southeast in STEREO A COR2A before a large data gap after 2025-12-04T12:48Z. Likely associated with a narrow eruption from near the central meridian near Active Region 14298 (S16E02) with a minor eruption that deflects sharply to the west.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge, plane of sky measurement using SOHO C2 frames only.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 associated with a rising plume of plasma and field line movement around 2025-12-04T19:30Z with additional movement occurring after 20:00Z seen best high off the east limb in GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using only SOHO C2/C3 and knowledge of the source location to approximate the longitude.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source may be moving field lines and filament ejecta observed over the SW limb in GOES SUVI 171/195/284/304 starting around 2025-12-05T00:40Z, and as filament ejecta just on/beyond the SW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 starting at 2025-12-05T01:45Z after a data gap. Alternative source could be a minor eruption located at ~120 degrees longitude, as seen in STEREO A EUV 195 imagery starting ~2025-12-05T01:55Z as minor post-eruptive arcades.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C3 only plane-of-sky.

cmes.note: Faint but clear loop seen in multiple timestamps of STEREO A COR2. We potentially can see a super faint NNE front in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-05T07:48Z, but the front is not seen in C3 and GOES CCOR-1 (possibly because it is too faint). No clear source has been found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very speculative analysis based on the fit of the faint but clear loop-like front in STEREO A COR2 and the extremely faint fuzzy half-loop front that might be seen in SOHO LASCO C2 in a number of early timeframes to the NNE.

cmes.note: CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and to the SE in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely an eruption from AR 14298 starting around 2025-12-05T07:36Z, observed as brightening and field line movement in GOES SUVI 131/171/195/284/304 centered around S12W16. Also observed as brightening from this region in STEREO A EUVI 195/304 on the SE disk as viewed from STEREO A.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1) and supporting a minor eruption in AR 14298 as a likely source.
Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Very faint narrow jet seen to the E in SOHO LASCO but not seen in STEREO A COR2. Source for it has not been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: The CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph and no source for it is seen in EUV imagery, so only a plane-of-sky analysis can be made.

cmes.note: Faint narrow jet to the E in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and possibly seen to the SE after a data gap ending on 2025-12-05T20:08Z in STEREO A COR2. Its source is likely far-sided, indicated by faint opening of field lines on/behind the east limb seen around 2025-12-05T17:56Z seen in GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit of this very narrow fronts in two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). The source is behind the east limb and cannot confirm the longitude of the fit.

cmes.note: Faint loop directed NE in STEREO A COR2 and potentially seen super faintly as a very fuzzy NNE front dissipating after a couple of timestamps in SOHO LASCO C2. It is likely too faint to be seen in C3 and in GOES CCOR-1. The CME has two consecutive fronts, with the earlier one possibly being the shock. (This CME resembles the 2025-12-05T07:09Z CME seen in COR2A to the NE). The start of this CME may actually be earlier as the quality of earlier COR2 imagery is poor. Possible source is a narrow filament eruption in AR 14299 (N23E19) seen in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-12-05T16:08Z, clearly directed northward of this active region (possible northward deflection).

cmeAnalyses.note: Very speculative analysis based on the fit of a second faint but clear loop front seen in STEREO A COR2 and the extremely faint fuzzy front that can be discerned in SOHO LASCO C2 in early timestamps.

cmes.note: CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and faintly, to the NW, for one frame in STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an eruption from an active region seen near the NW limb from the point of view of STEREO A, at approximately N20W135. Opening field lines are visible starting around 2025-12-05T18:05Z in STEREO A EUV 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, based on the potential source location. The CME is not measurable in STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME seen to the NW in GOES CCOR-1. The CME is also faintly visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The source is not found, and is likely farsided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky measurement using GOES CCOR-1 running difference imagery in SWPC_CAT.

cmes.note: CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and faintly in GOES CCOR-1. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The potential source is an eruption near the west limb, around N05W80, starting around 2025-12-06T01:32Z, best seen in GOES SUVI 304 and STEREO A EUV 304 as brightening and material leaving the disk. Moving/opening field lines are also best seen in GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on source location using SOHO LASCO C2 imagery only. The CME was not measurable in other running difference imagery.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-06T19:36Z. This CME is also seen to the WNW in GOES CCOR-1 and to the W in STEREO A COR2. It is obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is possibly related to an eruption seen in STA EUVI 304 starting around 2025-12-06T16:45Z that is most likely former AR 14288 which rotated off the Earth-facing disk on 2025-12-03.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best-fit measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 as well as probable source location seen in STA EUVI 304.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2. The CME is also seen in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is most likely associated with an M1.1 flare from AR 14299 that peaked at 2025-12-06T19:21Z. The flare an accompanying eruption can be seen across GOES wavelengths but is best seen in GOES SUVI 304 and GOES SUVI 131.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best-fit measurement based on triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 as well as visible source.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the E in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-12-06T20:53Z. The CME is also seen as a full halo in SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this CME is most likely an M8.1 flare from AR 14299 (N23E02) that peaked at 2025-12-06T20:39Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Preliminary BULK measurement based on early frames from STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2.
SHOCK measurement based on triangulation of SHOCK feature among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: This narrow, faint, jet-like CME is visible to the E/SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There are two potential sources for this CME which may indicated overlapping CME features of two separate CMEs. However, due to the available viewpoints, it is unclear if there are overlapping CMEs headed to the E/SE in all coronagraphs. The sources include a small filament eruption visible along the E/SE limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-12-07T05:00Z with liftoff closer to 2025-12-07T06:00Z, or the more likely source of an area of brightening visible in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-12-07T05:52Z near S10E50 with an area of brightening to the north of it. These two eruptions appear to be sympathetic eruptions and may be magnetically connected to each other.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to poor image quality; the CME does not appear to match any source imagery on the Earth-facing disk, and is thus probably associated with a far-sided source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge plane of sky measurement using SOHO, as the source longitude is unknown.

cmes.note: Narrow, diffuse CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 around 2025-12-07T22:00Z; associated with a minor eruption near western limb with northward deflection seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-12-07T20:48Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using approximation of the source based on source EUV imagery

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-08T01:25Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is minor field line opening and dimming seen at approx. N50E20 beginning at approx. 2025-12-08T00:24Z as seen in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: First visible in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-12-08T01:38Z already well into the FOV of COR2A following a data gap. The source is most likely associated with an M2.4 flare from AR 14299 that peaked at 2025-12-08T00:12Z and the accompanying eruption beginning around 2025-12-08T00:00Z that is best visible in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on fit in STEREO A COR2 with visible source location.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-08T05:00Z. This CME is also seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely a small filament eruption from near the SE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-12-08T04:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement to the E (-90 lon.) chosen due to lack of available triangulation.

cmes.note: CME first seen with the bulk to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-08T05:12Z. This CME is also seen to the NW in GOES CCOR-1 and to the NNE in STEREO A COR2. It is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is most likely related to an X1.1 flare from AR 14298 that peaked at 2025-12-08T05:01Z. The flare and associated eruption are best seen in GOES SUVI 304. The ejecta from the eruption experiences visible northward deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit of widest part of the bulk in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-12-08T07:24Z. This CME is also seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1. The front may also be faintly seen for a couple of frames in STEREO A COR2. This CME is most likely associated with an M1.8 flare from AR 14299 that peaked at 2025-12-08T06:54Z. The flare and accompanying ejecta can best be seen in GOES SUVI 304. The ejecta appears to be deflected northward.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-12-08T14:40Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This CME appears to have a much wider half width in STEREO A compared to in SOHO and GOES. The source of this event is an eruption from the vicinity of Active Region 14299 (N21W21), beginning at approx. 2025-12-08T14:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 195. There also appears to be a channel of dimming that travels to the North of the initial eruption, which suggests a Northward deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is likely associated with an M1.2 flare from AR 14299 (N26W30) peaking at 2025-12-08T22:28Z, observed in GOES SUVI 131. Also observed as brightening and field line movement in GOES SUVI 171/195/284.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 only analysis, as the CME travels into the LASCO C3 pylon and STEREO A COR2 is in a data gap. Using the flare source at N26W30 (AR 14299) as the source, could vary around W20-W40 and N20-N30.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-12-08Y23:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This CME is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen for this event, aside from some minor field line movement seen along the Western limb in GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approx. 2025-12-08T22:28Z which may be related.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using a longitude of +90 degrees due to unclear source location and lack of STEREO A COR2 imagery to triangulate.

cmes.note: CME with a somewhat fuzzy front seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1, catching up/overlapping with 2025-12-08T23:24Z CME. The corresponding front is likely seen to the NE in STEREO A COR2 starting from 2025-12-09T01:38Z. The front in COR2 is a bit more clear/pronounced than in SOHO and CCOR-1. The source of this CME is completely clear but might be the eruption and M2.0 flare from Active Region 14299 (N22W25). The CME is seen in C2 a bit earlier than the start of the flare, however the dimming is seen starting prior to the start of the flare.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2), if we are correct regarding the corresponding fronts.

cmes.note: Extremely faint minor CME seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 and not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. The likely corresponding front in STEREO A COR2 is very faintly seen to the N starting after 2025-12-09T01:53Z. No clear source has been found for this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit of the faint front with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). No source has been found in EUV imagery to confirm this analysis.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-12-09T03:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1 and to the SE in STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This source of this event is a minor M1.1 flare from Active Region 14294 (S19E41) which peaked at 2025-12-09T01:38Z. This flare is visible in GOES SUVI 131, along with a narrow curved ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304, some field line opening and Southeastern stretching dimming seen in GOES SUVI 195, suggesting some Southeastern deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Very faint, narrow jet-like front seen in difference imagery of SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 and too faint to be seen in white light imagery and in difference imagery of SOHO LASCO C3. The CME somewhat resembles CME: 2025-12-09T00:12Z but is narrower and fainter. It is not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source for it has been found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since the CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph and no source has been found for it, only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the NW by GOES CCOR-1 beginning at 2025-12-09T16:15Z, as well as by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is not available in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in real time due to a downlink data gap beginning at 2025-12-09T11:15Z. The source of this event is minor field line opening seen originating from the vicinity of N35W20 beginning at approx. 2025-12-09T15:09Z, exhibiting some Northern deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the SW in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. The CME is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to a data gap starting at 2025-12-09T11:00Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption from beyond the western limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-19-09T18:04Z. Moving/opening field lines along the W/SW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-12-09T16:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Preliminary parameters based on best fit using GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.
